Here's the complete migration. The code has three `Thread.Abort`-dependent patterns that all need replacement:

## Pattern Analysis

| .NET Framework Pattern | Problem in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Called `Thread.Abort` internally — throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Just return the result from the action |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `true` = endResponse, called `Thread.Abort` | Return `Redirect()` result |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in .NET 8 — dead code | Remove entirely |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8 ASP.NET Core)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // No Response.Clear/Write/End — return a FileResult instead.
        // The framework handles Content-Disposition and streaming.
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAfterProcess()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // No endResponse parameter — just return the redirect.
            // Execution continues normally; no Thread.Abort.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // ThreadAbortException catch is REMOVED — it is never thrown
        // in .NET 8. Do NOT port it as catch (OperationCanceledException)
        // here because redirects don't throw OCE either.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

**1. Don't just remove `true` from `Response.Redirect`** — in ASP.NET Core there is no `Response.Redirect` that ends execution. You must `return` a `RedirectResult` so code after it doesn't execute.

**2. Don't replace `catch (ThreadAbortException)` with `catch (OperationCanceledException)`** — the redirect path doesn't involve cancellation. That catch block was only needed because `Response.Redirect(url, true)` threw `ThreadAbortException` as a side effect. With `return Redirect(...)`, no exception is thrown at all.

**3. `Response.End()` has no equivalent** — the ASP.NET Core pipeline doesn't support aborting the response mid-action. Return a result object (`FileResult`, `ContentResult`, etc.) and let the framework write the response.

**4. Null-check `User.Identity`** — in ASP.NET Core, `User.Identity` can be `null` when no authentication middleware has run. The original code assumed it was always non-null.

**5. For long-running reports**, accept `CancellationToken` to honor client disconnects:

```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> Export(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // ASP.NET Core automatically wires this to HttpContext.RequestAborted
    var data = await GenerateReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
    return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```

This replaces the old `Response.End()` abort-the-thread model with cooperative cancellation — the `GenerateReportAsync` method checks the token at regular intervals and throws `OperationCanceledException` if the client disconnects.
